library(powerjoin)
library(glue)
if (!dir.exists("data")) {
  dir.create("data")
}
root <- 'https://gdex.ucar.edu/dataset/camels/file'
types <- c("clim", "geol", "soil", "topo", "vege", "hydro")
remote_files <- glue('{root}/camels_{types}.txt')
local_files  <- glue('data/camels_{types}.txt')
walk2(remote_files, local_files, download.file, quiet = TRUE)

camels_list <- map(local_files, read_delim, show_col_types = FALSE)

camels <- power_full_join(camels_list, by = "gauge_id")

camels_recipe <- recipe(q_mean ~ aridity + p_mean, data = camels_train) %>%
  step_log(all_numeric_predictors(), base = 10) %>%
  step_naomit(all_predictors(), all_outcomes())

linear_model <- linear_reg() %>%
  set_engine("lm") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

rf_model <- rand_forest(mtry = 2, trees = 500) %>%
  set_engine("ranger") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

boosted_model <- boost_tree(trees = 1000, tree_depth = 6, min_n = 10) %>%
  set_engine("xgboost") %>%
  set_mode("regression")

model_workflows <- workflow_set(

  models = list(
    linear = linear_model,
    random_forest = rf_model,
    xgboost = boosted_model

#The random forest model performed the best, with the lowest rmse (0.50) and the highest rsq (0.89), indicating strong predictive accuracy and variance explanation. It outperformed both the linear model and boosted tree, making it the best choice for predicting `q_mean`. Random forests are well-suited for capturing complex, nonlinear relationships in the data, which likely contributed to its strong performance.

#I chose the random forest model because this type of model builds many decision trees and then averages their results. It uses the "ranger" engine and works in regression mode. This model is probably doing well because it can find complex patterns and relationships between things like `aridity` and `p_mean`, which are important for predicting streamflow (`q_mean`). Itâs also good at handling messy data and doesnât overfit easily, which makes it a good fit for this kind of hydrologic data.
